## A Shortcut Formula for \(\sigma^{2}\)

The number of arithmetic operations necessary to compute \(\sigma^{2}\) can be reduced by using an alternative computing formula.

### Proposition

\[V(X)=\sigma^{2}=\left[\sum_{D}x^{2}\cdot p(x)\right]-\mu^{2}=E(X^{2})-\left[E( X)\right]^{2}\]

In using this formula, \(E(X^{2})\) is computed first without any subtraction; then \(E(X)\) is computed, squared, and subtracted (once) from \(E(X^{2})\).

Referring back to the Apgar score scenario of Examples 3.16 and 3.23,

\[E(X^{2})=\sum_{x=0}^{10}x^{2}\cdot p(x)=(0^{2})(.002)+(1^{2})(.001)+...+(10^{2} )(.01)=52.704\]

Thus \(\sigma^{2}=52.704-(7.15)^{2}=1.5815\) as before.

