\[\begin{array}{c}M_{X}^{\prime}(t)=.2e^{t}+.1(2)e^{2t}\\ M_{X}^{\prime\prime}(t)=.2e^{t}+.1(2)(2)e^{2t}\\ \end{array}\]

Setting \(t\) to \(0\) in the first derivative gives the first moment

\[E(X)=M_{X}^{\prime}(0)=M_{X}^{(1)}(0)=.2e^{0}+.1(2)e^{2(0)}=.2+.1(2)=.4\]

Setting \(t\) to \(0\) in the second derivative gives the second moment

\[E(X^{2})=M_{X}^{\prime\prime}(0)=M_{X}^{(2)}(0)=.2e^{0}+.1(2)(2)e^{2(0)}=.2+.1 (2)(2)=.6\]

To get the variance recall the shortcut formula from the previous section:

\[V(X)=\sigma^{2}=E(X^{2})-\left[E(X)\right]^{2}=.6-.4^{2}=.6-.16=.44\]

Taking the square root gives \(\sigma=.66\) approximately. Do a mean of \(.4\) and a standard deviation of \(.66\) seem about right for a distribution concentrated mainly on \(0\) and \(1\)? \(\blacksquare\)

