### Obtaining \(f(x)\) from \(F(x)\)

For \(X\) discrete, the pmf is obtained from the cdf by taking the difference between two \(F(x)\) values. The continuous analog of a difference is a derivative. The following result is a consequence of the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus.

\begin{tabular}{c c}  & \\ PROPOSITION & If \(X\) is a continuous rv with pdf \(f(x)\) and cdf \(F(x)\), then at every \(x\) at which the derivative \(F^{\prime}(x)\) exists, \(F^{\prime}(x)=f(x)\). \\ \end{tabular}

When \(X\) has a uniform distribution, \(F(x)\) is differentiable except at \(x=A\) and \(x=B\), where the graph of \(F(x)\) has sharp corners. Since \(F(x)=0\) for \(x<A\) and \(F(x)=1\) for \(x>B\), \(F^{\prime}(x)=0=f(x)\) for such \(x\). For \(A<x<B\),

\[F^{\prime}(x)=\frac{d}{dx}\left(\frac{x-A}{B-A}\right)=\frac{1}{B-A}=f(x)\]

