## The Normal Distribution and Discrete Populations

The normal distribution is often used as an approximation to the distribution of values in a discrete population. In such situations, extra care must be taken to ensure that probabilities are computed in an accurate manner.

IQ (as measured by a standard test) is known to be approximately normally distributed with \(\mu=100\) and \(\sigma=15\). What is the probability that a randomly selected individual has an IQ of at least 125? Letting \(X=\) the IQ of a randomly chosen person, we wish \(P(X\geq 125)\). The temptation here is to standardize \(X\geq 125\) immediately as in previous examples. However, the IQ population is actually discrete, since IQs are integer-valued, so the normal curve is an approximation to a discrete probability histogram, as pictured in Figure 4.24.

