## 4.7 Transformations of a Random Variable

Often we need to deal with a transformation \(Y=g(X)\) of the random variable \(X\). Here \(g(X)\) could be a simple change of time scale. If \(X\) is in hours and \(Y\) is in minutes, then \(Y=60X\). What happens to the pdf when we do this? Can we get the pdf of \(Y\) from the pdf of \(X\)? Consider first a simple example.

The interval \(X\) in minutes between calls to a 911 center is exponentially distributed with mean 2 min, so has pdf \(f_{X}(x)=\frac{1}{2}e^{-x/2}\) for \(x>0\). Can we find the pdf of \(Y=60X\), so \(Y\) is the number of seconds? In order to get the pdf, we first find the cdf. The cdf of \(Y\) is

\[F_{Y}(y) =P(Y\leq y)=P(60X\leq y)=P(X\leq y/60)=F_{X}(y/60)\] \[=\int_{0}^{y/60}\frac{1}{2}e^{-u/2}du=1-e^{-y/120}.\]

Differentiating this with respect to \(y\) gives \(f_{Y}(y)=(1/120)e^{-y/120}\) for \(y>0\). The distribution of \(Y\) is exponential with mean 120 s (2 min).

Sometimes it isn't possible to evaluate the cdf in closed form. Could we still find the pdf of \(Y\) without evaluating the integral? Yes, and it involves differentiating the integral with respect to the upper limit of integration. The rule, which is sometimes presented as part of the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, is

\[\frac{d}{dx}\int_{q}^{x}h(u)du=h(x).\]Now, setting \(x=y/60\) and using the chain rule, we get the pdf using the rule for differentiating integrals:

\[f_{Y}(y) = \left.\frac{d}{dy}F_{Y}(y)=\frac{d}{dy}F_{X}(x)\right|_{x=y/60}= \frac{dx}{dy}\frac{d}{dx}F_{X}(x)\right|_{x=y/60}\] \[= \left.\frac{1}{60}\frac{d}{dx}\int_{0}^{x}\frac{1}{2}e^{-u/2}du= \frac{1}{60}\cdot\frac{1}{2}e^{-x/2}=\frac{1}{120}\ e^{-y/120}\right.\]

Although it is useful to have the integral expression of the cdf here for clarity, it is not necessary. A more abstract approach is just to use differentiation of the cdf to get the pdf. That is, with \(x=y/60\) and again using the chain rule,

\[f_{Y}(y) = \left.\frac{d}{dy}F_{Y}(y)=\frac{d}{dy}F_{X}(x)\right|_{x=y/60}= \frac{dx}{dy}\frac{d}{dx}F_{X}(x)=\frac{1}{60}f_{X}(x)\] \[= \frac{1}{60}\cdot\frac{1}{2}e^{-x/2}=\frac{1}{120}\ e^{-y/120} \ \ y>0.\]

Is it plausible that, if \(X\sim\) exponential with mean 2, then \(60X\sim\) exponential with mean 120? In terms of time between calls, if it is exponential with mean 2 min, then this should be the same as exponential with mean 120 s. Generalizing, there is nothing special here about 2 and 60, so it should be clear that if we multiply an exponential random variable with mean \(\mu\) by a positive constant \(c\) we get another exponential random variable with mean \(c\mu\). This is also easily verified using a moment generating function argument.

The method illustrated above can be applied to other transformations.

