\begin{tabular}{p{28.5pt} p{28.5pt}} \hline \hline DEFINITION & Two random variables \(X\) and \(Y\) are said to be **independent** if for every pair of \(x\) and \(y\) values, \\  & \(p(x,y)=p_{X}(x)\cdot p_{Y}(y)\)  when \(X\) and \(Y\) are discrete \\ or & (5.1) \\  & \(f(x,y)=f_{X}(x)\cdot f_{Y}(y)\) when \(X\) and \(Y\) are continuous \\ \end{tabular} If (5.1) is not satisfied for all (\(x\), \(y\)), then \(X\) and \(Y\) are said to be **dependent**.

The definition says that two variables are independent if their joint pmf or pdf is the product of the two marginal pmf's or pdf's.

