This proposition says that \(\rho\) is a measure of the degree of **linear** relationship between \(X\) and \(Y\), and only when the two variables are perfectly related in a linear manner will \(\rho\) be as positive or negative as it can be. A \(\rho\) less than 1 in absolute value indicates only that the relationship is not completely linear, but there may still be a very strong nonlinear relation. Also, \(\rho=0\) does not imply that \(X\) and \(Y\) are independent, but only that there is complete absence of a linear relationship. When \(\rho=0\), \(X\) and \(Y\) are said to be **uncorrelated**. Two variables could be uncorrelated yet highly dependent because of a strong nonlinear relationship, so be careful not to conclude too much from knowing that \(\rho=0\).

