\[\mu_{X|Y=0} =E(X|Y=0)=100p_{X|Y}(100|0)+250p_{X|Y}(250|0)\] \[=100(.8)+250(.2)=130\] \[\sigma^{2}_{X|Y=0} =V(X|Y=0)=E\Big{(}[X-E(X|Y=0)]^{2}|Y=0\Big{)}\] \[=(100-130)^{2}p_{X|Y}(100|0)+(250-130)^{2}p_{X|Y}(250|0)\] \[=30^{2}(.8)+120^{2}(.2)=3600.\]Again, the conditional mean and variance are random because they depend on the random value of \(Y\). 

For any given weight of almonds, let's find the expected weight of cashews. Using the definition of conditional mean,

\[\mu_{Y|X=x} =E(Y|X=x)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}yf_{Y|X}(y|x)\,dy=\int_{0}^{1-x}y \,\frac{2y}{(1-x)^{2}}\,dy\] \[=\frac{2}{3}(1-x)\qquad 0\leq\,x\,\leq 1\]

The conditional mean is a linear decreasing function of \(x\). When there are more almonds, we expect less cashews. This is in accord with Figure 5.2, which shows that for large \(X\) the domain of \(Y\) is restricted to small values. To get the corresponding variance, compute first

\[E(Y^{2}|X=x)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}y^{2}f_{Y|X}(y|x)\,dy=\int_{0}^{1-x}y^{2} \frac{2y}{(1-x)^{2}}\,dy=\frac{(1-x)^{2}}{2}\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,0\leq x\leq 1\]

Then the conditional variance is

\[\sigma_{Y|X=x}^{2}=V(Y|X=x)=E\big{(}Y^{2}|X=x\big{)}-\mu_{Y|X=x}^{2}=\frac{(1- x)^{2}}{2}-\frac{4(1-x)^{2}}{9}=\frac{(1-x)^{2}}{18}\]

and the conditional standard deviation is

\[\sigma_{Y|X=x}=\frac{1-x}{\sqrt{18}}\]

