The sample mean \(\overline{X}\) and sample total \(T_{o}\) are special cases of a type of random variable that arises very frequently in statistical applications.

\begin{tabular}{c c} DEFINITION & Given a collection of \(n\) random variables \(X_{1}\), \(X_{2}\), \(\ldots\), \(X_{n}\) and \(n\) numerical constants \(a_{1}\), \(\ldots\), \(a_{n}\), the rv \\ \(Y=a_{1}X_{1}+\cdots+a_{n}X_{n}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}X_{i}\) \\ \end{tabular}

is called a **linear combination** of the \(X_{i}\)'s.

\begin{tabular}{c c} Taking & \(a_{1}=a_{2}=\cdot\cdot\cdot\cdot=a_{n}=1\) & gives & \(Y=X_{1}+\cdot\cdot\cdot\cdot+X_{n}=T_{\text{o}}\), and \(a_{1}=a_{2}=\cdot\cdot\cdot\cdot\cdot\cdot=a_{n}=\frac{1}{n}\) & yields \(Y=\frac{1}{n}X_{1}+\cdot\cdot\cdot+\frac{1}{n}X_{n}=\frac{1}{n}(X_{1}+\cdot \cdot\cdot+X_{n})=\frac{1}{n}T_{o}=\overline{X}\). Notice that we are not requiring the \(X_{i}\)'s to be independent or identically distributed. All the \(X_{i}\)'s could have different distributions and therefore different mean values and variances. We first consider the expected value and variance of a linear combination.

\begin{tabular}{c c} PROPOSITION & Let \(X_{1}\), \(X_{2}\), \(\ldots\), \(X_{n}\) have mean values \(\mu_{1}\), \(\ldots\), \(\mu_{n}\), respectively, and variances \(\sigma_{1}^{2},\ldots,\sigma_{n}^{2}\), respectively. \\ \end{tabular}

**1.** Whether or not the \(X_{i}\)'s are independent,

\[\begin{split} E(a_{1}X_{1}+\cdots+a_{n}X_{n})&=a_{1 }E(X_{1})+\cdots+a_{n}E(X_{n})\\ &=a_{1}\mu_{1}+\cdots+a_{n}\mu_{n}\end{split} \tag{6.7}\]

**2.**: If \(X_{1}\), \(\ldots\), \(X_{n}\) are independent,

\[\begin{split} V(a_{1}X_{1}+\cdots+a_{n}X_{n})&=a_{1}^{2 }V(X_{1})+\cdots+a_{n}^{2}V(X_{n})\\ &=a_{1}^{2}\sigma_{1}^{2}+\cdots+a_{n}^{2}\sigma_{n}^{2}\end{split} \tag{6.8}\]

and

\[\sigma_{a_{1}X_{1}+\cdots+a_{n}X_{n}}=\sqrt{a_{1}^{2}\sigma_{1}^{2}+\cdots+a_{n }^{2}\sigma_{n}^{2}} \tag{6.9}\]
**3.**: For any \(X_{1}\), \(X_{2}\), \(\ldots\), \(X_{n}\),

\[V(a_{1}X_{1}+\cdots+a_{n}X_{n})=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j=1}^{n}a_{i}a_{j}\text{ cov}(X_{i},X_{j}) \tag{6.10}\]

