The pdf of a random variable \(T\) having a \(t\) distribution with \(v\) degrees of freedom is

\[f(t)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}v}\,\frac{\Gamma[(v+1)/2]}{\Gamma(v/2)}\,\frac{1}{(1+t ^{2}/v)^{(v+1)/2}},\quad-\infty<t<\infty\]

We first find the cdf of \(T\) and then differentiate to obtain the pdf. A \(t\) variable is defined in terms of a standard normal \(Z\) and a chi-squared variable \(X\) with \(v\) degrees of freedom. They are independent, so their joint pdf \(f(x,z)\) is the product of their individual pdfs.

\[P(T\leq t)=P\left(\frac{Z}{\sqrt{X/v}}\leq t\right)=P\left(Z\leq t\sqrt{\frac{X }{v}}\right)=\int_{0}^{\infty}\int_{-\infty}^{v\sqrt{x/v}}f(x,z)\ dz\ dx\]

Differentiating with respect to \(t\) using the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus,

\[f(t)=\frac{d}{dt}P(T\leq t)=\int_{0}^{\infty}\frac{d}{dt}\int_{-\infty}^{v \sqrt{x/v}}f(x,z)\ dz\ dx=\int_{0}^{\infty}\sqrt{\frac{x}{v}}f\bigg{(}x,t\sqrt {\frac{x}{v}}\bigg{)}dx\]

Now substitute the joint pdf and integrate

\[f(t)=\int_{0}^{\infty}\sqrt{\frac{x}{v}}\frac{x^{v/2-1}}{2^{v/2}\Gamma(v/2)}e^ {-x/2}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\,e^{-r^{2}x/(2v)}dx\]

The integral can be evaluated by writing the integrand in terms of a gamma pdf.

\[f(t) = \frac{\Gamma[(v+1)/2]}{\sqrt{2\pi v}\Gamma(v/2)[1/2+t^{2}/(2v)]^{ [(v+1)/2]}2^{v/2}}\] \[\times\int_{0}^{\infty}\left(\frac{1}{2}+\frac{t^{2}}{2v}\right)^ {(v+1)/2}\frac{x^{(v+1)/2-1}}{\Gamma[(v+1)/2]}e^{-[1/2+t^{2}/(2v)]x}dx\]

The integral of the gamma pdf is 1, so

\[f(t) = \frac{\Gamma[(v+1)/2]}{\sqrt{2\pi v}\Gamma(v/2)[1/2+t^{2}/(2v)]^{ [(v+1)/2]}2^{v/2}}\] \[= \frac{\Gamma[(v+1)/2]}{\sqrt{\pi v}\Gamma(v/2)}\,\frac{1}{(1+t^{ 2}/v)^{[(v+1)/2]}},\quad-\infty<t<\infty\]The pdf has a maximum at 0 and decreases symmetrically as \(l\!l\) increases. As \(v\) becomes large the \(t\) pdf approaches the standard normal pdf, as shown in Exercise 54. It makes sense that the \(t\) distribution would be close to the standard normal for large \(v\), because \(T=Z/\sqrt{\chi_{v}^{2}/v}\), and \(\chi_{v}^{2}/v\) converges to 1 by the law of large numbers, as shown in Exercise 48.

