### Summary of Relationships

Is it clear how the standard normal, chi-squared, \(t\), and \(F\) distributions are related? Starting with a sequence of \(n\) independent standard normal random variables (let's use five, \(Z_{1},Z_{2},\ldots,Z_{5}\), to be specific) can we construct random variables having the other distributions? For example, the chi-squared distribution with \(n\) degrees of freedom is the sum of \(n\) independent standard normal squares, so \(Z_{1}^{2}+Z_{2}^{2}+Z_{3}^{2}\) has the chi-squared distribution with 3 degrees of freedom.

Recall that the ratio of a standard normal rv to the square root of an independent chi-squared rv, divided by its df \(v\), has the \(t\) distribution with \(v\) df. This implies that \(Z_{4}\Big{/}\sqrt{\big{(}Z_{1}^{2}+Z_{2}^{2}+Z_{3}^{2}\big{)}/3}\) has the \(t\) distribution with 3 degrees of freedom. Why would it be wrong to use \(Z_{1}\) in place of \(Z_{4}\)?

Building a random variable with the \(F\) distribution requires two independent chi-squared rvs. We already have \(Z_{1}^{2}+Z_{2}^{2}+Z_{3}^{2}\) with 3 df, and similarly we obtain \(Z_{4}^{2}+Z_{5}^{2}\), chi-squared with 2 df. Dividing each chi-square rv by its df and taking the ratio gives an \(F_{2,3}\) random variable, \(\big{[}\big{(}Z_{4}^{2}+Z_{5}^{2}\big{)}/2\big{]}/\big{[}\big{(}Z_{1}^{2}+Z_{ 2}^{2}+Z_{3}^{2}\big{)}/3\big{]}\).

