## Chapter 8 Confidence Intervals for the Variance and Standard Deviation of a Normal Population

Although inferences concerning a population variance \(\sigma^{2}\) or standard deviation \(s\) are usually of less interest than those about a mean or proportion, there are occasions when such procedures are needed. In the case of a normal population distribution, inferences are based on the following result from Section 6.4 concerning the sample variance \(S^{2}\).

\begin{tabular}{c c} THEOREM & Let \(X_{1}\), \(X_{2}\),..., \(X_{n}\) be a random sample from a normal distribution with parameters \(\mu\) and \(\sigma^{2}\). Then the rv \\  & \(\frac{(n-1)S^{2}}{\sigma^{2}}=\frac{\sum\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}\right)^{2}}{ \sigma^{2}}\) \\  & has a chi-squared (\(\chi^{2}\)) probability distribution with \(n\,-\,1\) df. \\ \end{tabular}

As discussed in Sections 4.4 and 6.4, the chi-squared distribution is a continuous probability distribution with a single parameter \(v\), the number of degrees of freedom, with possible values 1, 2, 3,.... To specify inferential procedures that use the chi-squared distribution, recall the notation for critical values from Section 6.4.

