Substituting the computed value \(s\)2 into the limits gives a CI for \(s\)2, and taking square roots gives an interval for \(s\)2.

A **100(1 - _a_)% confidence interval for the variance \(s\)2 of a normal population has lower limit

\[(n-1)s^{2}/\chi_{\alpha/2,n-1}^{2}\]

and upper limit

\[(n-1)s^{2}/\chi_{1-\alpha/2,n-1}^{2}\]

A **confidence interval for _s_** has lower and upper limits that are the square roots of the corresponding limits in the interval for \(s\)2.

