Now consider what happens when \(H_{0}\) is false because \(\mu=21\). We again had MINITAB generate 10,000 different samples of size 4, each from a normal distribution with \(\mu=21\) and \(\sigma=2\), calculate \(t=(\overline{x}-20)/(s/\sqrt{4})\) for each one, and then determine the \(P\)-value. The first such sample resulted in \(\overline{x}=20.6411\), \(s=.49637,\ t=2.5832,\ P\mbox{-value}=.0408\). Figure 9.9(b) gives a histogram of the 10,000 resulting \(P\)-values. The shape of this histogram is quite different from that of Figure 9.9(a): there is a much greater tendency for the \(P\)-value to be small (closer to 0) when \(\mu=21\) than when \(\mu=20\). Again \(H_{0}\) is rejected at significance level.05 whenever the \(P\)-value is at most.05 (in the first class interval). Unfortunately this is the case for only about 19% of the 10,000 \(P\)-values. So only about 19% of the 10,000 tests correctly reject the null hypothesis; for the other 81%, a type II error is committed. The difficulty is that the sample size is quite small and 21 is not very different from the value asserted by the null hypothesis.

