The Neyman-Pearson theorem says that when \(\Omega_{0}\) consists of a single value \(\theta_{0}\) and \(\Omega_{\text{a}}\) also consists of a single value \(\theta_{\text{a}}\), the rejection region \(R^{*}\) specifies a test for which the power \(\pi(\theta_{a})\) at the alternative value \(\theta_{\text{a}}\) (which is just \(1-\beta\)) is maximized subject to \(\pi(\theta_{0})\leq\alpha\) for some specified value of \(\alpha\). That is, \(R^{*}\) specifies a _most powerful test_ subject to the restriction on the power when the null hypothesis is true.

What about best tests when at least one of the two hypotheses is **composite**, that is, \(\Omega_{0}\) or \(\Omega_{a}\) (or both) consist of more than a single value?

Consider again a random sample of size \(n=5\) from a Poisson distribution, and suppose we now wish to test \(H_{0}\): \(\lambda\leq 1\) versus \(H_{\text{a}}\): \(\lambda>1\). Both of these hypotheses are composite. Arguing as in Example 9.20, for any value \(\lambda_{\text{a}}\) exceeding 1, a most powerful test of \(H_{0}\): \(\lambda=1\) versus \(H_{\text{a}}\): \(\lambda=\lambda_{\text{a}}\) with significance level (power when \(\lambda=1\)).032 rejects the null hypothesis when \(\Sigma x_{i}\geq 10\). Furthermore, it is easily verified that the power of this test at \(\lambda^{\prime}\) is smaller than.032 if \(\lambda^{\prime}<1\). Thus the test that rejects \(H_{0}\): \(\lambda\leq 1\) in favor of \(H_{0}\): \(\lambda>1\) when \(\Sigma x_{i}\geq 10\) has maximum power for _any_\(\lambda^{\prime}>1\) subject to the condition that \(\pi(\lambda^{\prime})\leq.032\). This test is _uniformly most powerful_. 

More generally, a **uniformly most powerful (UMP) level \(\alpha\) test** is one for which \(\pi(\theta^{\prime})\) is maximized for any \(\theta\in\Omega_{\text{a}}\) subject to \(\pi(\theta^{\prime})\leq\alpha\) for any \(\theta^{\prime}\in\Omega_{0}\). Unfortunately UMP tests are fairly rare, especially in commonly encountered situations when \(H_{0}\) and \(H_{\text{a}}\) are assertions about a single parameter \(\theta_{1}\) whereas the distribution of the \(X_{i}\)'s involves not only \(\theta_{1}\) but also at least one other "nuisance parameter". For example, when the population distribution is normal with values of both \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\) unknown, \(\sigma\) is a nuisance parameter when testing \(H_{0}\): \(\mu=\mu_{0}\) versus \(H_{a}\): \(\mu\neq\mu_{0}\). Be careful here--the null hypothesis is not simple because \(\Omega_{0}\) consists of all pairs (\(\mu\), \(\sigma\)) for which \(\mu=\mu_{0}\) and \(\sigma>0\), and there is certainly more than one such pair. In this situation, the one-sample \(t\) test is not UMP.

