### Likelihood Ratio Tests

The likelihood ratio (LR) principle is the most frequently used method for finding an appropriate test statistic in a new situation. As before, denote the joint pmf or pdf of \(X_{1}\), \(\ldots\), \(X_{n}\) by \(f(x_{1},\ldots,x_{n};\theta)\). In the case of a random sample, it will be a product \(f(x_{1};\theta)\cdot\cdots\cdot f(x_{n};\theta)\). When the \(x_{i}\)'s are the actual observations and \(f(x_{1},\ldots,x_{n};\theta)\) is regarded as a function of \(\theta\), it is called the _likelihood function_. Again consider testing \(H_{0}\): \(\theta\in\Omega_{0}\) versus \(H_{\text{a}}\): \(\theta\in\Omega_{\text{a}}\), where \(\Omega_{0}\) and \(\Omega_{\text{a}}\) are disjoint sets, and let \(\Omega=\Omega_{0}\cup\Omega_{\text{a}}\). In the Neyman-Pearson theorem, we focused on the ratio of the likelihood when \(\theta\in\Omega_{\text{a}}\) to the likelihood when \(\theta\in\Omega_{0}\), rejecting \(H_{0}\) when the value of the ratio was "sufficiently large". Now we consider the ratio of the likelihood when \(\theta\in\Omega_{0}\) to the likelihood when \(\theta\in\Omega\). A very _small_ value of this ratio argues against the null hypothesis, since a small value arises when the data is much more consistent with the alternative hypothesis than with the null hypothesis. More formally,

1. Find the largest value of the likelihood for any \(\theta\in\Omega_{0}\) by finding the maximum likelihood estimate of \(\theta\) within \(\Omega_{0}\) and substituting this mle into the likelihood function to obtain \(L(\hat{\Omega}_{0})\).
2. Find the largest value of the likelihood for any \(\theta\in\Omega\) by finding the maximum likelihood estimate of \(\theta\) within \(\Omega\) and substituting this mle into the likelihood function to obtain \(L(\hat{\Omega})\). Because \(\Omega_{0}\) is a subset of \(\Omega\), this likelihood \(L(\hat{\Omega})\) can't be any smaller than the likelihood \(L(\hat{\Omega}_{0})\) obtained in the first step, and will be much larger when the data is much more consistent with \(H_{\text{a}}\) than with \(H_{0}\).
3. Form the _likelihood ratio_\(L(\hat{\Omega}_{0})/L(\hat{\Omega})\)and reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative when this ratio is \(\leq k\). The critical value \(k\) is chosen to give a test with the desired significance level. In practice, the inequality \(L(\hat{\Omega}_{0})/L(\hat{\Omega})\leq k\) is often re-expressed in terms of a more convenient statistic (such as the sum of the observations) whose distribution is known or can be derived. The above prescription remains valid if the single parameter \(\theta\) is replaced by several parameters \(\theta_{1}\), \(\ldots\), \(\theta_{k}\). The mle's of all parameters must be obtained in both steps 1 and 2 and substituted back into the likelihood function.

Consider a random sample from a normal distribution with the values of both parameters unknown. We wish to test \(H_{0}\): \(\mu=\mu_{0}\) versus \(H_{\text{a}}\): \(\mu\neq\mu_{0}\). Here \(\Omega\) consists of all values of \(\mu\) and \(\sigma^{2}\) for which \(-\infty<\mu<\infty\) and \(\sigma^{2}>0\), and the likelihood function is

\[\left(\frac{1}{2\pi\sigma^{2}}\right)^{n/2}e^{-1/(2\sigma^{2})\sum{(x_{i}-\mu )^{2}}}\]In Section 7.2 we obtained the mle's as \(\hat{\mu}=\uppi,\ \hat{\sigma}^{2}=\sum\left(x_{i}-\uppi\right)^{2}/n\). Substituting these estimates back into the likelihood function gives

\[L(\hat{\Omega})=\left(\frac{1}{2\pi\sum\left(x_{i}-\uppi\right)^{2}/n}\right)^{ n/2}e^{-n/2}\]

Within \(\Omega_{0}\), \(\mu\) in the foregoing likelihood is replaced by \(\mu_{0}\), so that only \(\sigma^{2}\) must be estimated. It is easily verified that the mle is \(\hat{\sigma}^{2}=\sum\left(x_{i}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}/n\). Substitution of this estimate in the likelihood function yields

\[L(\hat{\Omega}_{0})=\left(\frac{1}{2\pi\sum\left(x_{i}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}/n} \right)^{n/2}e^{-n/2}\]

Thus we reject \(H_{0}\) in favor of \(H_{\text{a}}\) when

\[\frac{L(\hat{\Omega}_{0})}{L(\hat{\Omega})}=\left(\frac{\sum\left(x_{i}-\uppi \right)^{2}}{\sum\left(x_{i}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}}\right)^{n/2}\leq k\]

Raising both sides of this inequality to the power \(2/n\), we reject \(H_{0}\) whenever

\[\frac{\sum\left(x_{i}-\uppi\right)^{2}}{\sum\left(x_{i}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}} \leq k^{2/n}=k^{\prime}\]

This is intuitively quite reasonable: the value \(\mu_{0}\) is implausible for \(\mu\) if the sum of squared deviations about the sample mean is much smaller than the sum of squared deviations about \(\mu_{0}\). The denominator of this latter ratio can be expressed as

