The probability of a type II error is easily calculated when both population distributions are normal with known values of \(\sigma_{1}\) and \(\sigma_{2}\). Consider the case in which the alternative hypothesis is \(H_{\text{a}}\): \(\mu_{1}-\mu_{2}>\Delta_{0}\). Let \(\Delta^{\prime}\) denote a value of \(\mu_{1}-\mu_{2}\) that exceeds \(\Delta_{0}\) (a value for which \(H_{0}\) is false). The upper-tailed rejection region \(z\geq z_{\text{a}}\) can be re-expressed in the form \(\overline{x}-\overline{y}\geq\Delta_{0}+z_{\text{a}}\sigma_{\overline{x}- \overline{y}}\). Thus the probability of a type II error when \(\mu_{1}-\mu_{2}=\Delta^{\prime}\) is

\[\beta(\Delta^{\prime}) =P(\text{not rejecting }H_{0}\text{ when }\mu_{1}-\mu_{2}= \Delta^{\prime})\] \[=P(\overline{X}-\overline{Y}<\Delta_{0}+z_{\text{a}}\sigma_{ \overline{X}-\overline{Y}}\text{ when }\mu_{1}-\mu_{2}=\Delta^{\prime})\]

When \(\mu_{1}-\mu_{2}=\Delta^{\prime},\overline{X}-\overline{Y}\) is normally distributed with mean value \(\Delta^{\prime}\) and standard deviation \(\sigma_{\overline{X}-\overline{Y}}\) (the same standard deviation as when \(H_{0}\) is true); using these values to standardize the inequality in parentheses gives \(\beta\).

