A permutation test for paired data involves permutations within the pairs. Under the null hypothesis, the two observations in a pair have the same population mean, so the population mean difference is zero, even if the order is reversed. Therefore, we consider all possible orderings of the \(n\) pairs. Because there are two possible orderings within each pair, there are \(2^{n}\) arrangements of \(n\) pairs. The one-tailed \(P\)-value is the fraction of the \(2^{n}\) differences that are at least as extreme as the observed value, and the two-tailed \(P\)-value is double this.

