## Models for Random Effects

In many experiments, the actual levels of a factor used in the experiment, rather than being the only ones of interest to the experimenter, have been selected from a much larger population of possible levels of the factor. In a two-factor situation, when this is the case for both factors, a **random effects model** is appropriate. The case in which the levels of one factor are the only ones of interest and the levels of the other factor are selected from a population of levels leads to a **mixed effects model**. The two-factor random effects model when \(K_{ij}=1\) is

\[X_{ij}=\mu+A_{i}+B_{j}+\varepsilon_{ij}\qquad(i=1,...,I;\quad j=1,...,J)\]

where the \(A_{i}\)'s, \(B_{j}\)'s, and \(\varepsilon_{ij}\)'s are all independent, normally distributed rv's with mean 0 and variances \(\sigma_{A}^{2}\),\(\sigma_{B}^{2}\), and \(\sigma^{2}\), respectively.

The hypotheses of interest are then \(H_{0A}\): \(\sigma_{A}^{2}=0\) (level of factor \(A\) does not contribute to variation in the response) versus \(H_{\rm{aA}}\): \(\sigma_{A}^{2}>0\) and \(H_{0B}\): \(\sigma_{B}^{2}=0\) versus \(H_{\rm{aB}}\): \(\sigma_{B}^{2}>0\). Whereas \(E({\rm{MSE}})=\sigma^{2}\) as before, the expected mean squares for factors \(A\) and \(B\) are now

\[E({\rm{MSA}})=\sigma^{2}+J\sigma_{A}^{2}\quad E({\rm{MSB}})=\sigma^{2}+I\sigma _{B}^{2}\]

Thus when \(H_{0A}\) (H\({}_{\rm{OB}}\)) is true, \(F_{A}(F_{B})\) is still a ratio of two unbiased estimators of \(\sigma^{2}\). It can be shown that a test with significance level \(\alpha\) for \(H_{0A}\) versus \(H_{\rm{aA}}\) still rejects \(H_{0A}\) if \(f_{A}\geq F_{\alpha J-1,(I-1)(J-1)}\), and, similarly, the same procedure as before is used to decide between \(H_{0B}\) and \(H_{\rm{aB}}\).

For the case in which factor \(A\) is fixed and factor \(B\) is random, the mixed model is

\[X_{ij}=\mu+\alpha_{i}+B_{j}+\varepsilon_{ij}\qquad(i=1,...,I;\quad j=1,...,J)\]

where \(\sum\alpha_{i}=0\), and the \(B_{j}\)'s, and \(\varepsilon_{ij}\)'s are all independent, normally distributed rv's with mean 0 and variances \(\sigma_{B}^{2}\) and \(\sigma^{2}\), respectively.

