## Covariance Matrices

In order to develop hypothesis tests and confidence intervals for the regression coefficients, the standard deviations of the estimated coefficients are needed. These can be obtained from a certain _covariance matrix_, a matrix with the variances on the diagonal and the covariances in the off-diagonal elements. If \(\mathbf{U}\) is a column vector of random variables \(U_{1},\ldots\), \(U_{n}\) with means \(\mu_{1}=E(U_{1}),\ldots,\mu_{n}=E(U_{n})\), let \(\mathbf{\mu}\) be the vector of these \(n\) means and define

\[\text{Cov}(\mathbf{U}) = \begin{bmatrix}\text{Cov}(U_{1},U_{1})&\cdots&\text{Cov}(U_{1},U_ {n})\\ \vdots&\ddots&\vdots\\ \text{Cov}(U_{n},U_{1})&\cdots&\text{Cov}(U_{n},U_{n})\end{bmatrix}\] \[= \begin{bmatrix}E[(U_{1}-\mu_{1})(U_{1}-\mu_{1})]&\cdots&E[(U_{1}- \mu_{1})(U_{n}-\mu_{n})]\\ \vdots&\ddots&\vdots\\ E[(U_{n}-\mu_{n})(U_{1}-\mu_{1})]&\cdots&E[(U_{n}-\mu_{n})(U_{n}-\mu_{n})]\end{bmatrix}\] \[= E\left\{\begin{bmatrix}U_{1}-\mu_{1}\\ \vdots\\ U_{n}-\mu_{n}\end{bmatrix}[U_{1}-\mu_{1},\ \cdots\,U_{n}-\mu_{n}]\right\} = E\{[\mathbf{U}-\mathbf{\mu}][\mathbf{U}-\mathbf{\mu}]^{\prime}\}\]

When \(n=1\) this reduces to just the ordinary variance. The key to finding the needed covariance matrix is this proposition:

\[\text{PROPOSITION}\]

If \(A\) is a matrix with constant entries and \(\mathbf{V}=\mathbf{A}\mathbf{U}\), then \(\text{Cov}(\mathbf{V})=\mathbf{A}\text{Cov}(\mathbf{U})\mathbf{A}^{\prime}\).

ProofBy the linearity of the expectation operator, \(E(\mathbf{V})=E(\mathbf{A}\mathbf{U})=\mathbf{A}E(\mathbf{U})\). Then

\[\text{Cov}(\mathbf{V}) = E\big{\{}[\mathbf{A}\mathbf{U}-E(\mathbf{A}\mathbf{U})][\mathbf{A}\mathbf{U}-E(\mathbf{A}\mathbf{ U})]^{\prime}\big{\}}=E\{\mathbf{A}[\mathbf{U}-E(\mathbf{U})](\mathbf{A}[\mathbf{U}-E(\mathbf{U})])^{ \prime}\}\] \[= E\big{\{}\mathbf{A}[\mathbf{U}-E(\mathbf{U})][\mathbf{U}-E(\mathbf{U})]^{\prime}\mathbf{ A}^{\prime}\big{\}}\] \[= AE\big{\{}[\mathbf{U}-E(\mathbf{U})][\mathbf{U}-E(\mathbf{U})]^{\prime}\big{\}} \mathbf{A}^{\prime}=\mathbf{A}\text{Cov}(\mathbf{U})\mathbf{A}^{\prime}\]

Let's apply the proposition to find the covariance matrix of \(\hat{\mathbf{\beta}}\). Because \(\hat{\mathbf{\beta}}=[\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1}\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{Y}\), we use \(\mathbf{A}=[\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1}\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\) and \(\mathbf{U}=\mathbf{Y}\). The transpose of \(\mathbf{A}\) is \(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}=\{[\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1}\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\}^{\prime}=\mathbf{ X}[\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1}\). The covariance matrix of \(\mathbf{Y}\) is just the variance \(\sigma^{2}\) times the \(n\)-dimensional identity matrix, that is, \(\sigma^{2}\mathbf{I}\), because the observations are independent and all have the same variance \(\sigma^{2}\). Then the proposition says

\[\text{Cov}(\hat{\mathbf{\beta}})=\mathbf{A}\text{Cov}(\mathbf{Y})\mathbf{A}^{\prime}=[\mathbf{X}^{ \prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1}\mathbf{X}^{\prime}[\sigma^{2}\mathbf{I}]\mathbf{X}[\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{ X}]^{-1}=\sigma^{2}[\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1} \tag{12.24}\]We also need to find the expected value of \(\hat{\mathbf{\beta}}\),

\[E(\hat{\mathbf{\beta}}) =E([\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1}\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{Y})=[\mathbf{X}^{ \prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1}\mathbf{X}^{\prime}E(\mathbf{Y})\] \[=[\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1}\mathbf{X}^{\prime}E(\mathbf{X}\mathbf{\beta}+\bm {\varepsilon})=[\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1}\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}\mathbf{\beta}=\bm {\beta}\]

That is, \(\hat{\mathbf{\beta}}\) is an unbiased estimator of \(\mathbf{\beta}\) (for each \(i\), \(\hat{\beta}_{i}\) is unbiased for estimating \(\beta_{i}\)).

Write the inverse matrix as \([\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1}=\mathbf{C}=[c_{ij}]\). In particular, let \(c_{00},c_{11},\ldots,c_{kk}\) be the diagonal elements of this inverse matrix. Then \(V(\hat{\beta}_{j})=\sigma^{2}c_{ij}\). Also, \(\hat{\beta}_{j}\) is a linear combination of \(Y_{1}\),..., \(Y_{n}\), which are independent normal, so \((\hat{\beta}_{j}-\beta_{j})/(\sigma\sqrt{c_{ij}})\sim N(0,1)\) It follows that (this requires the independence of \(S\) and the estimated regression coefficients, which we will not prove) \((\hat{\beta}_{j}-\beta_{j})/(S\sqrt{c_{ij}})\sim t_{n-(k+1)}\). This leads to the confidence interval and hypothesis test for coefficients of Section 12.7.

The 95% confidence interval for \(\beta_{j}\) is

\[\hat{\beta}_{j}\pm t_{.025,n-(k+1)}s\sqrt{c_{ji}}. \tag{12.25}\]

We can test the hypothesis \(H_{0}\): \(\beta_{j}=\beta_{j0}\) using the \(t\) ratio

\[T=\quad\frac{\hat{\beta}_{j}-\beta_{j0}}{S\sqrt{c_{ij}}}\sim t_{n-(k+1)}\]

Statistical software packages usually provide output for testing \(H_{0}\)\(\beta_{j}=0\) against the two-sided alternative \(H_{\text{a}}\): \(\beta_{j}\neq 0\). In particular, we would reject \(H_{0}\) in favor of \(H_{\text{a}}\) at the 5% level if \(\mathfrak{l}\mathfrak{l}\) exceeds \(t_{.025,n-(k+1)}\). Usually, with computer output there is no need to use statistical tables for hypothesis tests because \(P\)-values for these tests are included.

For the engine horsepower scenario we found that \(s=7.002\), \(\hat{\beta}_{0}=-61.417\), \(\hat{\beta}_{1}=95.5\), \(\hat{\beta}_{2}=33\) and \([\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1}\) has elements \(c_{00}=79/12\), \(c_{11}=1\), \(c_{22}=2/3\). Therefore, we get these 95% confidence intervals:

\[\hat{\beta}_{1}\pm t_{.025,6-(2+1)}s\sqrt{c_{11}}=95.5\pm 3.182(7.002) \sqrt{1}=95.50\pm 22.28=[73.22,117.78]\] \[\hat{\beta}_{2}\pm t_{.025,6-(2+1)}s\sqrt{c_{22}}=33\pm 3.182(7.002) \sqrt{2/3}=33\pm 18.19=[14.81,51.19]\]

We can also do the individual \(t\) tests for the coefficients:

\[\frac{\hat{\beta}_{1}-0}{s\sqrt{c_{11}}}=\frac{95.5-0}{7.002\sqrt {1}}=13.64,\qquad\text{two-tailed $P$-value}=.0009\] \[\frac{\hat{\beta}_{2}-0}{s\sqrt{c_{22}}}=\frac{33-0}{7.002\sqrt{2 /3}}=5.77,\quad\text{two-tailed $P$-value}=.0103\]

Both of these exceed \(t_{.025,6-2-1}=3.182\) in absolute value (and their \(P\)-values are less than.05), so for both of them we reject at the 5% level the null hypothesis that the coefficient is \(0\), in favor of the two-sided alternative. These conclusions are consistent with the fact that the corresponding confidence intervals do not include zero. Also, recall that the \(F\) test rejected at the 5% level the null hypothesis that both coefficients are zero. As our intuition suggests, horsepower increases with engine size and horsepower is higher when the engine requires premium fuel.

## The Hat Matrix

The foregoing proposition can be used to find estimated standard deviations for predicted values and residuals. Recall that the vector of predicted values can be obtained by multiplying the hat matrix \(\mathbf{H}\) times the \(\mathbf{Y}\) vector, \(\mathbf{HY}=\hat{\mathbf{Y}}\). First, in order to apply the proposition, let's obtain the transpose of \(\mathbf{H}\). With the help of the rules \((\mathbf{AB})^{\prime}=\mathbf{B}^{\prime}\mathbf{A}^{\prime}\) and \((\mathbf{A}^{-1})^{\prime}=(\mathbf{A}^{\prime})^{-1}\), we find that \(\mathbf{H}\) is symmetric, \(\mathbf{H}^{\prime}=\mathbf{H}\):

\[\mathbf{H}^{\prime}=\Big{\{}\mathbf{X}[\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1}\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\Big{\}} ^{\prime}=(\mathbf{X}^{\prime})^{\prime}\{[\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1}\}^{\prime} \mathbf{X}^{\prime}=\mathbf{X}\big{\{}[\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}]^{\prime}\,\}^{-1}\mathbf{X}^ {\prime}=\mathbf{X}[\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1}\mathbf{X}^{\prime}=\mathbf{H}.\]

Therefore,

\[\begin{split}\text{Cov}(\hat{\mathbf{Y}})&=\mathbf{H}\text{ Cov}(\mathbf{Y})\mathbf{H}^{\prime}=\mathbf{X}[\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1}\mathbf{X}^{\prime}[ \sigma^{2}I]\mathbf{X}[\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1}\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\\ &=\sigma^{2}\mathbf{X}[\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\mathbf{X}]^{-1}\mathbf{X}^{\prime}= \sigma^{2}\mathbf{H}.\end{split} \tag{26}\]

A similar calculation shows that the covariance matrix of the residuals is

\[\text{Cov}(\mathbf{Y}-\hat{\mathbf{Y}})=\sigma^{2}(\mathbf{I}-\mathbf{H}) \tag{27}\]

Of course, the true variance \(\sigma^{2}\) is generally unknown, so the estimate \(s^{2}=\text{MSE}\) is used instead.

