### Goodness of Fit for Discrete Distributions

Many experiments involve observing a random sample \(X_{1}\), \(X_{2}\), \(\ldots\), \(X_{n}\) from some discrete distribution. One may then wish to investigate whether the underlying distribution is a member of a particular family, such as the Poisson or negative binomial family. In the case of both a Poisson and a negative binomial distribution, the set of possible values is infinite, so the values must be grouped into \(k\) subsets before a chi-squared test can be used. The groupings should be done so that the expected frequency in each cell (group) is at least 5. The last cell will then correspond to \(X\) values of \(c\), \(c+1\), \(c+2\), \(\ldots\) for some value \(c\).

