### The Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Interval

To test \(H_{0}\colon\mu=\mu_{0}\) versus \(H_{\mathrm{a}}\colon\mu\neq\mu_{0}\) using the Wilcoxon signed-rank test, where \(\mu\) is the mean of a continuous symmetric distribution, the absolute values \(|x_{1}-\mu_{0}|,\ldots,|x_{n}-\mu_{0}|\) are ordered from smallest to largest, with the smallest receiving rank 1 and the largest, rank \(n\). Each rank is then given the sign of its associated \(x_{i}-\mu_{0}\), and the test statistic is the sum of the positively signed ranks. The two-tailed test rejects \(H_{0}\) if \(s_{+}\) is either \(\geq c\) or \(\leq n(n+1)/2-c\), where \(c\) is obtained from Appendix Table A.12 once the desired level of significance \(\alpha\) is specified. For fixed \(x_{1}\), \(\ldots\), \(x_{n}\), the 100(1 \(-\)\(\alpha\))% signed-rank interval will consist of all \(\mu_{0}\) for which \(H_{0}\colon\mu=\mu_{0}\) is not rejected at level \(\alpha\). To identify this interval, it is convenient to express the test statistic \(S_{+}\) in another form.

\begin{tabular}{c c} \(S_{+}=\) & the number of pairwise averages \(\bigl{(}X_{i}+X_{j}\bigr{)}/2\) with \(i\leq j\) \\  & that are \(\geq\mu_{0}\) \\ \end{tabular}  (14.4)

